{{Infobox U.S. legislation | shorttitle = Agent Orange Act of 1991 | othershorttitles = | longtitle = An Act to provide for the Secretary of Veterans Affairs to obtain independent scientific review of the available scientific evidence regarding associations between diseases and exposure to dioxin and other chemical compounds in herbicides, and for other purposes. | colloquialacronym = AOA | nickname = Agent Orange bill | enacted by = 102nd | effective date = February 6, 1991 | public law url = http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/STATUTE-105/pdf/STATUTE-105-Pg11.pdf | cite public law = 102-4 | cite statutes at large = {{usstat|105|11}} | acts amended = | acts repealed = | title amended = [[Title 38 of the United States Code|38 U.S.C.: Veterans' Benefits]] | sections created = {{usc|38|1116}} | sections amended = {{unbulleted list|{{usc|38|101}} et seq.|{{usc|38|241}}|{{usc|38|1154}}}} | leghisturl = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d102:HR00556:@@@R | introducedin = House | introducedbill = {{USBill|102|H.R.|556}} | introducedby = [[Gillespie V. Montgomery]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]–[[Mississippi|MS]]) | introduceddate = January 17, 1991 | committees = [[United States House Committee on Veterans' Affairs|House Veterans' Affairs]] | passedbody1 = House | passeddate1 = January 29, 1991 | passedvote1 = 412-0 {{US House Vote|1991|016}} | passedbody2 = Senate | passedas2 = <!-- used if the second body changes the name of the legislation --> | passeddate2 = January 30, 1991 | passedvote2 = 99-0 {{US Senate Vote|102|1|9}}, in lieu of {{USBill|102|S.|238}} | conferencedate = | passedbody3 = | passeddate3 = | passedvote3 = | agreedbody3 = <!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee --> | agreeddate3 = <!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee --> | agreedvote3 = <!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee --> | agreedbody4 = <!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation --> | agreeddate4 = <!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation --> | agreedvote4 = <!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation --> | passedbody4 = | passeddate4 = | passedvote4 = | signedpresident = George H.W. Bush | signeddate = February 6, 1991 | unsignedpresident = <!-- used when passed without presidential signing --> | unsigneddate = <!-- used when passed without presidential signing --> | vetoedpresident = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | vetoeddate = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddenbody1 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddendate1 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddenvote1 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddenbody2 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddendate2 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddenvote2 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | amendments = | SCOTUS cases = }} '''Agent Orange Act of 1991''' establishes provisions for the [[National Academy of Sciences]] to analyze and summarize [[scientific evidence]] regarding presumptive [[military service]] exposure to [[defoliant]]s, [[Polychlorinated dibenzodioxins|dioxins]] and [[herbicide]]s, better known as [[Agent Orange]], during the [[Vietnam War]] [[era]]. The [[United States Statutes at Large|United States Statute]] endorses an observation of human medical conditions directly related to [[non-Hodgkin lymphoma]], [[soft-tissue sarcoma]], [[chloracne]], and consistent [[Acneiform eruption|acneform]] diseases for [[military personnel]] who served in the [[overseas Vietnamese]] region. The [[Act of Congress]] ratifies a [[medical research]] compilation of voluntarily contributed [[blood]] and [[Tissue (biology)|tissue]] [[Sampling (medicine)|samples]] provided by [[Vietnam veteran|Vietnam-era veterans]] serving in [[Southeast Asia]] between 1961 and 1975.
The H.R. 556 [[legislation]] was passed by the 102nd United States Congressional session and enacted into law by the [[Presidency of George H. W. Bush|41st President of the United States]] [[George H.W. Bush]] on February 6, 1991.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=19283 |title= George Bush: "Statement on Signing the Agent Orange Act of 1991," February 6, 1991 |author1=Peters, Gerhard |author2=Woolley, John T |publisher = University of California - Santa Barbara |work= The American Presidency Project}}</ref>
==History== =====''Agent Orange Study''===== On December 6, 1979, the [[96th United States Congress]] passed the ''Veterans Health Programs Extension and Improvement Act of 1979'' which was enacted into law by United States President Jimmy Carter on December 20, 1979.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/STATUTE-93/pdf/STATUTE-93-Pg1092.pdf |title=Veterans Health Programs Extension and Improvement Act of 1979 ~ P.L. 96-151 |date=December 20, 1979 |series=93 Stat. 1092 ~ House Bill 3892 |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office}}</ref> House Bill 3892 endorsed the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] to conduct an [[Epidemiology|epidemiological]] study concerning [[Exposure assessment|human exposure]] and the adverse health effects of [[Dioxins and dioxin-like compounds|dioxins]] and [[Phenoxy herbicide|phenoxy herbicides]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/96th-congress/house-bill/3892 |title=H.R. 3892 ~ Veterans Health Programs Extension and Improvement Act of 1979 |date=May 2, 1979 |series=P.L. 96-151 ~ 93 Stat. 1092 |publisher=Congress.gov}}</ref> The [[persistent, bioaccumulative and toxic substances]] [[Protocol (science)|protocol]] was subject to approval by the [[Office of Technology Assessment]] as stated in the provisions of the H.R. 3892 legislation.
The 96th United States Senate passed bill S. 2096 sanctioning the Agent Orange study to be conducted by the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|United States Department of Health, Education, and Welfare]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/96th-congress/senate-bill/2096 |title=S. 2096 ~ Agent Orange Study of 1979 |date=December 20, 1979 |publisher=Congress.gov}}</ref> On January 2, 1980, President Jimmy Carter vetoed the Senate bill due to the repetitive purpose of the Section 307a1 provisions as stated in House bill 3892.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/node/250557 |title=Jimmy Carter: "Message to the Senate Returning S. 2096 Without Approval," January 2, 1980 |author1=Peters, Gerhard |author2=Woolley, John T |publisher=University of California - Santa Barbara |work=The American Presidency Project}}</ref>
