'''Bhishma Ashtami''' (Bhishmashtami) is a [[Hindu]] festival dedicated to [[Bhishma]] of the great Indian epic ''[[Mahabharata]]''. It is believed that Bhishma, also known as 'Ganga Putr Bhism' or 'Bhishma Pitamaha', departed from his soul on this chosen day. This occurred during the propitious 'Uttarayan period'; that is, the daytime of devas. Bhishma Ashtami is observed during the month of [[Magha (month)|Magha]] in the [[Hindu calendar]]. It corresponds to the months of January–February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hindu-blog.com/2009/01/bhisma-ashtami-bhismashtami.html|title=Bhisma Ashtami 2018 date – Importance of Bhisma Ashtami Snan - Tarpan - Vrat|website=www.hindu-blog.com|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref>
==History== Bhishma Ashtami is a minor holiday observed in [[Bengal]] and parts of southern India in remembrance of Bhishma, a warrior who fought and died in the [[Kurukshetra War]], the battle which fills so many pages of the [[Mahabharata]]. Bhishma was the son of [[Shantanu]], who had given his son a boon in that he would be allowed to choose his own day of death. Bhishma had taken an oath not to marry and that he would ever remain faithful to his father's throne.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KDU30Ae4S4cC&pg=PA114&dq=bhishma+ashtami&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiX5Lzu2rnTAhVKOSYKHeBpCrYQ6AEIIjAA#v=onepage&q=bhishma%20ashtami&f=false|title=Religious Celebrations: An Encyclopedia of Holidays, Festivals, Solemn Observances, and Spiritual Commemorations|last=Melton|first=J. Gordon|date=2011-09-13|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=|isbn=9781598842050|location=|pages=113–114|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hindu-blog.com/2009/01/bhisma-ashtami-bhismashtami.html|title=Bhisma Ashtami 2018 date – Importance of Bhisma Ashtami Snan - Tarpan - Vrat|website=www.hindu-blog.com|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref>
The anniversary of Bhishma Pitamah's death is observed during Magha Shukla Ashtami{{clarify|date=May 2017}}. The day is known as Bhishma Ashtami and indisputably the death anniversary of Bhishma Pitamah. According to the legend associated with the day, Bhishma waited for 58 days before leaving his body. Bhishma Pitamah left his body on the auspicious day of Uttarayana, i.e. on the day when the Lord Surya started moving towards Northward after completing six month period of Dakshiyana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.drikpanchang.com/festivals/bhishma-ashtami/info/bhishma-pitamah-death-time.html|title=Death Anniversary of Bhishma Pitamah {{!}} Death Chronology of Bhishma Pitamah|last=LLP|first=Adarsh Mobile Applications|website=www.drikpanchang.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>
This is the day Bhishma decided to leave his body. The day Bhishma left his body known as Bhishma Ashtami (Magha Shukla Ashtami). He has special boon of death as per his will (Ichha Mrityu) from his father. Hence, despite lying on a bed of arrows he continued in that position and then left his body on Sankranti. Hindus believe that the one who dies during Uttarayana goes to heaven.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b2iyCAAAQBAJ&pg=PT30&dq=bhishma+ashtami&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixxLHPmcHTAhUL0YMKHahoAQ8Q6AEINDAD#v=onepage&q=bhishma%20ashtami&f=false|title=Hindu Prayers, Gods and Festivals|last=Tumuluru|first=Kamal Kumar|date=2015-04-23|publisher=Partridge Publishing|isbn=9781482847079|language=en}}</ref>
==Bhishma Ashtami Festival Dates Between 2017 & 2024== {| class="wikitable" !Year !Date |- |2017 |Saturday, 4 February |- |2018 |Thursday, 25 January |- |2019 |Wednesday, 13 February |- |2020 |Sunday, 2 February |- |2021 |Saturday, 20 February |- |2022 |Tuesday, 8 February |- |2023 |Saturday, 28 January |- |2024 |Friday, 16 February |}
==Steps to Follow the Performance of 'Bhishma Ashtami Pujan'== * People observe the ritual of ‘Ekodishta Shraddha’ in the honor of Bhishma. According to the belief, only those devotees whose fathers are not alive anymore can perform this ritual. However, some communities do not follow this and believe that anyone can perform the ‘pooja’. * People visit the nearby river banks and do the ‘Tarpan’ ritual in order to bring peace to Bhishma Pitamah’s soul. They also honor their ancestors through the same ritual. * People take holy dips in the [[Ganga river]] and offer boiled rice and sesame seeds in order to come out of the cycle of life and death and purify their souls. * Devotees observe fast during the day and perform ‘Arghyam’ and chant ‘Bhishma Ashtami mantra’ to seek the deity’s blessings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pandit.com/bhishma-ashtami-rituals-in-india/|title=Bhishma Ashtami rituals in India - Pandit.com|website=www.pandit.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref>
