The '''European Youth Capital''' (abbreviated '''EYC''') is the title awarded to a [[Europe]]an city for the period of one year, during which it is given the chance to showcase, through a multi-faceted programme, its youth-related cultural, social, political and economic life and development.<ref name="EYC main"> {{Cite web|url=http://www.youthforum.org/CAPITAL/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=63&Itemid=68 |title=ABOUT THE EYC |publisher=www.youthforum.org/CAPITAL |accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref> The European Youth Capital is an initiative by the [[European Youth Forum]], and the first capital was chosen in 2009. Since 2014, the [[Congress of the Council of Europe|Congress of Local and Regional Authorities]] of the [[Council of Europe]] is an official endorsing partner the European Youth Capital title. The current, capital for the 2018 calendar year is [[Cascais]].
==Goals== The European Youth Capital aims in promoting intra-European co-operation between young people. Among the most important aspects of the institution is the betterment of everyday life of the youth in the city selected as youth capital, not just for the duration of the festivities, but in the long term.<ref name="EYC general information">{{Cite web|url=http://www.youthforum.org/CAPITAL/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=73:about&catid=35 |title=General Information |publisher=www.youthforum.org/CAPITAL |accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref> Additionally, participation of the youth in the design and implementation of the plans for each capital of youth is encouraged by the EYC.<ref name="EYC general information" /> Ensuring that the youth are informed and actively involved in society and given opportunities for a better future is also a priority for the EYC initiative.<ref name="EYC main" /> Tourism and increased international prestige are some of the additional benefits of being named European Youth Capital.<ref name="EYC main" />
==Capitals (2009–2021)== Since 2009, there have been next European Youth Capitals:<ref name="EYC past capitals">{{Cite web|url=http://www.youthforum.org/CAPITAL/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=64&Itemid=69 |title=EYCs of the Past, Present and Future |publisher=www.youthforum.org/CAPITAL |accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref><ref>http://www.europeanyouthcapital.org/yfj/varna-bulgaria-awarded-european-youth-capital-2017/ Varna (Bulgaria) awarded European Youth Capital 2017, 20 November, 2014</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=And the winner is: Cascais, EYC 2018!|url=http://www.europeanyouthcapital.org/yfj/european-youth-capital-2018-cascais/|accessdate=16 December 2015|work=europeanyouthcapital.org|date=3 December 2015}}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" |+European Youth Capital ! Year !! City !! Country !! Notes |- | 2009 || [[Rotterdam]] || {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Netherlands]] || |- | 2010 || [[Turin]] || {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Italy]] || |- | 2011 || [[Antwerp]] || {{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Belgium]] || |- | 2012 || [[Braga]] || {{flagicon|Portugal}} [[Portugal]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20160109081810/http://bragacej2012.com/ Info] |- | 2013 || [[Maribor]] || {{flagicon|Slovenia}} [[Slovenia]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130829144205/http://www.mb2013.si/en/ Info] |- | 2014 || [[Thessaloniki]] || {{flagicon|Greece}} [[Greece]] || [http://www.thessaloniki2014.eu/ Info] finalists: {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Ivanovo]], {{flagicon|Greece}} [[Heraklion]], other candidates: {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Barcelona]], {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Perm]], {{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Konya]], {{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Trabzon]] |- | 2015 || [[Cluj-Napoca]] || {{flagicon|Romania}} [[Romania]] || [http://www.cluj2015.eu/ Info] finalists: {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Ivanovo]], {{flagicon|Lithuania}} [[Vilnius]], {{flagicon|Bulgaria}} [[Varna]] other candidates: {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Katowice]], {{flagicon|Spain}} [[La Laguna]], {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Badajoz]], {{flagicon|Azerbaijan}} [[Ganja, Azerbai