{{Azeris}} {{see also|Culture of Azerbaijan}}
[[File:Изображение 1175.jpg|thumb|Azerbaijani youth celebrating Novruz.]] '''[[Nowruz|Novruz]] in [[Azerbaijan]]''' ({{lang-az|Novruz Bayramı}}) is a traditional holiday, which celebrates the New Year, and the coming of Spring. When Azerbaijan was part of the [[Soviet Union]], celebration of Novruz was generally unofficial, and at times even prohibited.<ref>{{citation|title=What exactly is Novruz Bayram|periodical=Azerbaijan Today|last=Waters|first=Zena|issue=12|accessdate=2009-03-22|url=http://www.azerbaijantoday.az/ARCHIVE/12/life1.html|date=April–May 2005}}</ref> Currently in Azerbaijan, [[Novruz]] is treated as an official public holiday. In accordance with Article 105 of the Labour Code of Azerbaijan passed in 2006, workers receive five days off for Novruz.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.deloitte.com/dtt/cda/doc/content/December_2006%20Tax%20and%20Legal%20News(2).pdf|periodical=Tax and Legal News|publisher=[[Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu]]|date=December 2006|accessdate=2009-03-22|title=Public Holidays in Azerbaijan}}</ref> After neighbouring Iran, Azerbaijan hosts the longest observance and amount of public days related to Novruz, with thus a total (including weekend) of 7 days.<ref name="Azerbaijan 2010 Bank Holidays">{{cite web|url=http://www.bank-holidays.com/holidays.php?annee=2010&id_pays=16 |title=Azerbaijan 2010 Bank Holidays |publisher=Bank-holidays.com |accessdate=2010-04-06}}</ref>
==Novruz customs and celebration== Usually preparation for Novruz begins a month prior to the festival. Each of forthcoming 4 weeks is devoted to one of the four elements and called accordingly in Azerbaijan. Each Tuesday people celebrate the day of one of the four elements - water, fire, earth and wind.<ref name=nowaze>[http://www.azerembassy-kuwait.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=167:international-day-of-nowruz-21-march-&catid=8:news-a-events&Itemid=37 International Day of Nowruz- 21 March] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513014137/http://www.azerembassy-kuwait.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=167:international-day-of-nowruz-21-march-&catid=8:news-a-events&Itemid=37 |date=2011-05-13 }}</ref> People do house cleaning, plant trees, make new dresses, paint eggs, make national pastries such as [[shekerbura]], [[pakhlava]], shorgoghal and a great variety of [[Azerbaijani cuisine|national cuisine]].<ref>[http://en.trend.az/news/official/chronicle/1657130.html Azerbaijan marks Novruz holiday ]</ref> Wheat is fried with kishmish ([[raisins]]) and [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]] (govurga). As a tribute to pre-Islamic [[Zoroastrian]] beliefs, every Tuesday during four weeks before the holiday children jump over small bonfires and candles are lit. On the holiday eve the graves of relatives are visited and tended.<ref>[http://www.everyculture.com/A-Bo/Azerbaijan.html Azerbaijani traditions]</ref>
Different ancient traditional games and shows such as “Kos-kosa” (symbolizes the coming of spring), “Khidir Ilyas” (the symbol of fertility and blossom), fortune telling, etc. are held at musical gatherings take place at Novruz holiday. Folk singers sing songs, the wrestlers test their strength. <ref>https://www.azernews.az/nation/51095.html</ref> <ref>http://azeriamerica.com/Events_files/AzeriHolidays.htm</ref>
Novruz is a family holiday. In the evening before the holiday the whole family gathers around the holiday table laid with various dishes to make the New Year rich. The holiday goes on for several days and ends with festive public dancing and other entertainment of folk bands, contests of national sports. In rural areas crop holidays are marked.<ref>[http://www.studentsoftheworld.info/sites/arts/3559.php Studentsoftheworld - Azeri Traditions]</ref>
The decoration of the festive table is khoncha, a big silver or copper tray with [[Semeni|Samani]], green shoots from wheat seeds placed in the centre and candles and dyed eggs by the number of family members around it. The table should be set, at least, with seven dishes.<ref name=nowaze />
