The '''Tainan fake panda incident''' refers to an incident at a private zoo in [[Tainan]], [[Taiwan]], where a [[sun bear]] was painted black and white and falsely presented to visitors as a [[Giant Panda]]. The bear was first unveiled on 24 December 1987, and quickly drew skepticism as experts were not permitted to enter the enclosure, and the pattern of spots on the fur appeared to change. The Tainan District Prosecutors Office sent investigators on December 31, suspecting fraud. By 3 January 1988, officials from the Council of Agriculture, and zoology experts from [[National Taiwan University]] and [[Normal University]] determined the animal was not a true panda.<ref>{{cite book|title="Selling Genuine Panda"(賣點100－真假熊-{}-猫))|year=1989|publisher=Yuan-Liou Publishing (遠流出版)|isbn=9789573201878|pages=41–43}}</ref>
This incident made popular the use of the term "(giant) cat bear" [''(dà)māoxióng'', (大)貓熊] instead of "(giant) bear cat" [''(dà)xióngmāo'', (大)熊貓] to refer to pandas in Taiwan.<ref>http://projectgen-y.com/2015/3a/misniwan/index.php/name/</ref>
==Links== * [https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=zh-CN&tl=en&js=y&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&u=https%3A%2F%2Fzh.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2F%25E5%258F%25B0%25E5%258D%2597%25E7%259C%259F%25E5%2581%2587%25E7%2586%258A%25E8%25B2%2593%25E4%25BA%258B%25E4%25BB%25B6&edit-text=&act=url Google Translation] of the original [[:zh-tw:台南真假熊貓事件|Chinese-language article]]
